# Claims first appearing in this paper. Leaf priors live in priors.py.

gcn_4d0e277c6d2c4cdc = claim(
    "In room-temperature angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) measurements on freshly cleaved single crystals of CsPbBr3, the hole effective mass at the valence-band maximum (VBM) located at the bulk Brillouin-zone R point was determined by fitting local quadratic dispersions and found to be m_{h}^{*}=0.203\\pm0.016\\,m_{0}, where m_{0} denotes the free-electron mass; this reported value is the average of four independent measurements on four different cleaved samples that produced individual fitted masses of 0.19\\,m_{0}, 0.23\\,m_{0}, 0.20\\,m_{0}, and 0.19\\,m_{0}. The identification of the VBM at the bulk R point was made by photon-energy-dependent ARPES mapping of the perpendicular crystal momentum k_{\\perp}, and under the free-electron final-state mapping k_{\\perp}=\\sqrt{\\tfrac{2m_{0}}{\\hbar^{2}}\\bigl(E_{\\mathrm{kin}}\\cos^{2}\\theta + V_{0}\\bigr)} with inner potential parameter V_{0}=5.3\\ \\mathrm{eV} (where \\hbar is the reduced Planck constant, E_{\\mathrm{kin}} the photoelectron kinetic energy referenced to the vacuum level, and \\theta the electron emission polar angle), the first R point in these measurements corresponds to photon energy h\\nu=29\\ \\mathrm{eV}. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="Sajedi ARPES mass 0.203",
    lkm_id="gcn_4d0e277c6d2c4cdc",
    lkm_original="In room-temperature angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) measurements on freshly cleaved single crystals of CsPbBr3, the hole effective mass at the valence-band maximum (VBM) located at the bulk Brillouin-zone R point was determined by fitting local quadratic dispersions and found to be m_{h}^{*}=0.203\\pm0.016\\,m_{0}, where m_{0} denotes the free-electron mass; this reported value is the average of four independent measurements on four different cleaved samples that produced individual fitted masses of 0.19\\,m_{0}, 0.23\\,m_{0}, 0.20\\,m_{0}, and 0.19\\,m_{0}. The identification of the VBM at the bulk R point was made by photon-energy-dependent ARPES mapping of the perpendicular crystal momentum k_{\\perp}, and under the free-electron final-state mapping k_{\\perp}=\\sqrt{\\tfrac{2m_{0}}{\\hbar^{2}}\\bigl(E_{\\mathrm{kin}}\\cos^{2}\\theta + V_{0}\\bigr)} with inner potential parameter V_{0}=5.3\\ \\mathrm{eV} (where \\hbar is the reduced Planck constant, E_{\\mathrm{kin}} the photoelectron kinetic energy referenced to the vacuum level, and \\theta the electron emission polar angle), the first R point in these measurements corresponds to photon energy h\\nu=29\\ \\mathrm{eV}.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_e17b013445234bfa = claim(
    "In angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) of a crystalline solid, the component of the electron crystal momentum perpendicular to the sample surface, k_{\\perp}, is commonly estimated from the incident photon energy h\\nu by the free-electron final-state approximation k_{\\perp}=\\sqrt{\\tfrac{2m_{0}}{\\hbar^{2}}\\bigl(E_{\\mathrm{kin}}\\cos^{2}\\theta + V_{0}\\bigr)}, where m_{0} is the free-electron mass, \\hbar is the reduced Planck constant, E_{\\mathrm{kin}} is the photoelectron kinetic energy measured with respect to the vacuum level (E_{\\mathrm{kin}}=h\\nu-\\phi-E_{B}, with \\phi the sample work function and E_{B} the electron binding energy), \\theta is the electron emission polar angle, and V_{0} is an inner-potential model parameter; applying this mapping with the model parameter V_{0}=5.3\\ \\mathrm{eV} assigns the photon energy h\\nu=29\\ \\mathrm{eV} to the first bulk R point in the perpendicular momentum coordinate for CsPbBr_{3} in the measurements reported here. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="Photon energy maps to R point",
    lkm_id="gcn_e17b013445234bfa",
    lkm_original="In angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) of a crystalline solid, the component of the electron crystal momentum perpendicular to the sample surface, k_{\\perp}, is commonly estimated from the incident photon energy h\\nu by the free-electron final-state approximation k_{\\perp}=\\sqrt{\\tfrac{2m_{0}}{\\hbar^{2}}\\bigl(E_{\\mathrm{kin}}\\cos^{2}\\theta + V_{0}\\bigr)}, where m_{0} is the free-electron mass, \\hbar is the reduced Planck constant, E_{\\mathrm{kin}} is the photoelectron kinetic energy measured with respect to the vacuum level (E_{\\mathrm{kin}}=h\\nu-\\phi-E_{B}, with \\phi the sample work function and E_{B} the electron binding energy), \\theta is the electron emission polar angle, and V_{0} is an inner-potential model parameter; applying this mapping with the model parameter V_{0}=5.3\\ \\mathrm{eV} assigns the photon energy h\\nu=29\\ \\mathrm{eV} to the first bulk R point in the perpendicular momentum coordinate for CsPbBr_{3} in the measurements reported here.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_ccc6a5bf10864de7 = claim(
    "For a valence band with energy dispersion E(k) as a function of crystal momentum k along a measured one-dimensional cut, the hole effective mass m_{h}^{*} at a local band maximum at k=k_{0} is obtained by fitting the local dispersion to a quadratic form E(k)\\approx E(k_{0})+\\tfrac{\\hbar^{2}}{2m_{h}^{*}}(k-k_{0})^{2} in a neighborhood of k_{0}; in this expression \\hbar denotes the reduced Planck constant, E(k_{0}) the band energy at the extremum, and k the momentum coordinate along the measured direction, and the extracted parameter m_{h}^{*} is the curvature-derived hole effective mass under the assumption that the actual band dispersion within the sampled momentum window is well approximated by a parabola. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="Quadratic fit extracts hole mass",
    lkm_id="gcn_ccc6a5bf10864de7",
    lkm_original="For a valence band with energy dispersion E(k) as a function of crystal momentum k along a measured one-dimensional cut, the hole effective mass m_{h}^{*} at a local band maximum at k=k_{0} is obtained by fitting the local dispersion to a quadratic form E(k)\\approx E(k_{0})+\\tfrac{\\hbar^{2}}{2m_{h}^{*}}(k-k_{0})^{2} in a neighborhood of k_{0}; in this expression \\hbar denotes the reduced Planck constant, E(k_{0}) the band energy at the extremum, and k the momentum coordinate along the measured direction, and the extracted parameter m_{h}^{*} is the curvature-derived hole effective mass under the assumption that the actual band dispersion within the sampled momentum window is well approximated by a parabola.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_3e860bd7f76e4767 = claim(
    "The experimental uncertainty reported for the ARPES-determined hole effective mass, \\pm 0.016\\,m_{0}, is the sample-to-sample standard deviation of four independent fitted effective-mass values obtained from four different freshly cleaved single-crystal samples (individual fitted values 0.19, 0.23, 0.20, and 0.19\\,m_{0}); this uncertainty is taken to represent the combined random and systematic uncertainty affecting the ARPES determination, where the principal systematic-error sources considered include photon-energy calibration, inner-potential selection, surface-condition variability after cleavage, analyzer angular calibration, and choice of fitting model, and the proposition is that these systematic contributions are either small compared to the observed sample-to-sample scatter or are effectively captured by the quoted standard deviation. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="ARPES mass uncertainty estimate",
    lkm_id="gcn_3e860bd7f76e4767",
    lkm_original="The experimental uncertainty reported for the ARPES-determined hole effective mass, \\pm 0.016\\,m_{0}, is the sample-to-sample standard deviation of four independent fitted effective-mass values obtained from four different freshly cleaved single-crystal samples (individual fitted values 0.19, 0.23, 0.20, and 0.19\\,m_{0}); this uncertainty is taken to represent the combined random and systematic uncertainty affecting the ARPES determination, where the principal systematic-error sources considered include photon-energy calibration, inner-potential selection, surface-condition variability after cleavage, analyzer angular calibration, and choice of fitting model, and the proposition is that these systematic contributions are either small compared to the observed sample-to-sample scatter or are effectively captured by the quoted standard deviation.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gfac_46ef4a3b05e946de = deduction(
    [gcn_e17b013445234bfa, gcn_ccc6a5bf10864de7, gcn_3e860bd7f76e4767],
    gcn_4d0e277c6d2c4cdc,
    reason="1. State the experimental technique and sample conditions used to determine the valence-band maximum (VBM) and the hole effective mass: angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) measurements were performed on freshly cleaved single crystals of CsPbBr$_{3}$ at room temperature with photon energies varied between $h\\nu=21\\,$eV and $h\\nu=83\\,$eV in 2 eV steps to map the electronic states as a function of the electron wave vector perpendicular to the surface $k_{\\perp}$, with spatial resolution $\\sim 100\\ \\mu$m and base pressure better than $2\\times10^{-10}$ mbar. \nFig. 2\n\n2. Define notation used for the measured quantity: denote the hole effective mass at the valence-band maximum by $m_{h}^{*}$ and the free-electron mass by $m_{0}$; the photon energy is $h\\nu$ and the perpendicular momentum is $k_{\\perp}$.\n\n3. Explain how the VBM (the R point) was identified from the photon-energy-dependent ARPES data: normal-emission (i.e., $\\overline{\\Gamma}$) photon-energy-dependent scans show symmetry about $k_{\\perp}=3.66\\ \\text{\\AA}^{-1}$ and the contours of constant binding energy near the VBM close at photon energies of $h\\nu=29\\,$eV and $h\\nu=54\\,$eV, which the authors therefore assign as the first and second R points; this assignment was corroborated by $k_{\\parallel}$-dependent contour plots near 1.5 eV binding energy (near the VBM) and by the observation of closing contours at the specified photon energies. The assignment corresponds to an inner potential $V_{0}=5.3\\,$eV for the R-point mapping (a different inner potential $V_{0}=9.6\\,$eV was used for an X/$\\Gamma$ assignment at normal emission). \nFig. 2\n\n4. State how the VBM photon energy was confirmed from the dispersion along the surface high-symmetry direction: band-dispersion cuts along $\\overline{\\Gamma}-\\overline{M}$ were taken at multiple photon energies and the binding-energy of the local maximum (related to the VBM) was evaluated as a function of photon energy; these data confirm $h\\nu=29\\,$eV as the photon energy at which the measured band reaches the VBM (R point) and show that the dispersion at $29\\,$eV appears narrower than at other photon energies. \nFig. 3\n\n5. Describe the procedure used to extract effective masses from the ARPES dispersions: for the band dispersion measured along $\\overline{\\Gamma}-\\overline{M}$ at the photon energy assigned to the VBM ($h\\nu=29\\,$eV), the authors fit the measured dispersion of the topmost valence band near its maximum to obtain a hole effective mass $m_{h}^{*}$ (the fitting procedure and fit of the dispersion are those used to produce the plotted effective masses versus photon energy). \nFig. 3\n\n6. Report the repeat measurements and fitted individual effective-mass values: the measurement at $h\\nu=29\\,$eV was repeated on four different cleaved single-crystal samples, yielding individual fitted hole effective masses of $0.19\\ m_{0}$, $0.23\\ m_{0}$, $0.20\\ m_{0}$, and $0.19\\ m_{0}$; these four values are those obtained from the dispersion fits for the topmost valence band at the assigned R point. \nFig. 3\n\n7. Compute and report the average and uncertainty: the average of the four repeated fitted values $0.19\\ m_{0}$, $0.23\\ m_{0}$, $0.20\\ m_{0}$, and $0.19\\ m_{0}$ is $0.203\\ m_{0}$ and the standard deviation is $\\pm 0.016\\ m_{0}$; therefore the experimentally determined hole effective mass at the VBM (R point) from ARPES is $m_{h}^{*}=0.203\\pm0.016\\ m_{0}$. \nFig. 3",
    prior=0.95,
)
gcn_8c3c520295d7488c = claim(
    "One-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle calculations that fully include relativistic spin–orbit coupling, performed for two structural models of CsPbBr3, yield the following valence-band hole effective masses and quasiparticle band gaps: for the cubic perovskite structure, an effective hole mass at the R point evaluated along the X–R direction of m_{h}^{*}=0.15\\,m_{0} with a quasiparticle band gap E_{\\mathrm{g}}^{\\mathrm{QP}}=1.74\\ \\mathrm{eV}; for an orthorhombic structural unit cell, a G_{0}W_{0} calculation (with the valence band Wannier-interpolated for the purpose of band-curvature averaging) yields an averaged hole effective mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} with quasiparticle band gap E_{\\mathrm{g}}^{\\mathrm{QP}}=2.09\\ \\mathrm{eV}. These one-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle results include electron–electron correlation effects via the GW self-energy but do not include electron–phonon self-energy contributions (i.e., they are bare-band quasiparticle properties with respect to phonons). [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="G0W0 bare masses for CsPbBr3",
    lkm_id="gcn_8c3c520295d7488c",
    lkm_original="One-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle calculations that fully include relativistic spin–orbit coupling, performed for two structural models of CsPbBr3, yield the following valence-band hole effective masses and quasiparticle band gaps: for the cubic perovskite structure, an effective hole mass at the R point evaluated along the X–R direction of m_{h}^{*}=0.15\\,m_{0} with a quasiparticle band gap E_{\\mathrm{g}}^{\\mathrm{QP}}=1.74\\ \\mathrm{eV}; for an orthorhombic structural unit cell, a G_{0}W_{0} calculation (with the valence band Wannier-interpolated for the purpose of band-curvature averaging) yields an averaged hole effective mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} with quasiparticle band gap E_{\\mathrm{g}}^{\\mathrm{QP}}=2.09\\ \\mathrm{eV}. These one-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle results include electron–electron correlation effects via the GW self-energy but do not include electron–phonon self-energy contributions (i.e., they are bare-band quasiparticle properties with respect to phonons).",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_ec768b9675814820 = claim(
    "In the orthorhombic-structure G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle calculation that produced the averaged hole effective mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0}, the construction of maximally-localized Wannier functions (Wannierization) was applied only to the valence-band manifold for the purpose of interpolating and averaging band curvatures whereas the conduction-band manifold was not Wannierized; this partial (valence-only) Wannier interpolation procedure can introduce a systematic bias in the interpolation of quasiparticle band curvatures and may lead to a modest overestimation of the reported averaged hole effective mass relative to a calculation in which both valence and conduction bands are treated consistently in the Wannier interpolation or in which no post-processing interpolation is used. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="Valence-only Wannier caveat",
    lkm_id="gcn_ec768b9675814820",
    lkm_original="In the orthorhombic-structure G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle calculation that produced the averaged hole effective mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0}, the construction of maximally-localized Wannier functions (Wannierization) was applied only to the valence-band manifold for the purpose of interpolating and averaging band curvatures whereas the conduction-band manifold was not Wannierized; this partial (valence-only) Wannier interpolation procedure can introduce a systematic bias in the interpolation of quasiparticle band curvatures and may lead to a modest overestimation of the reported averaged hole effective mass relative to a calculation in which both valence and conduction bands are treated consistently in the Wannier interpolation or in which no post-processing interpolation is used.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_5868b15c687043a9 = claim(
    "Numerical quasiparticle properties computed within the one-shot G_{0}W_{0} approximation, including the valence-band effective mass m_{h}^{*} and the quasiparticle band gap E_{\\mathrm{g}}^{\\mathrm{QP}}, are sensitive to specific computational choices and convergence parameters such as basis-set completeness, density and sampling of k points in the Brillouin zone, the frequency-integration scheme or plasmon-pole model used for the screened Coulomb interaction, the numerical treatment of spin–orbit coupling, details of pseudopotential versus all-electron implementations, and whether the GW calculation is performed as a single-shot (G_{0}W_{0}) or with partial self-consistency; consequently, different reasonable implementations or convergence thresholds of the G_{0}W_{0} method can produce quantitatively different values of m_{h}^{*} comparable to the differences observed between the cubic and orthorhombic calculations reported here. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="G0W0 method sensitivity caveat",
    lkm_id="gcn_5868b15c687043a9",
    lkm_original="Numerical quasiparticle properties computed within the one-shot G_{0}W_{0} approximation, including the valence-band effective mass m_{h}^{*} and the quasiparticle band gap E_{\\mathrm{g}}^{\\mathrm{QP}}, are sensitive to specific computational choices and convergence parameters such as basis-set completeness, density and sampling of k points in the Brillouin zone, the frequency-integration scheme or plasmon-pole model used for the screened Coulomb interaction, the numerical treatment of spin–orbit coupling, details of pseudopotential versus all-electron implementations, and whether the GW calculation is performed as a single-shot (G_{0}W_{0}) or with partial self-consistency; consequently, different reasonable implementations or convergence thresholds of the G_{0}W_{0} method can produce quantitatively different values of m_{h}^{*} comparable to the differences observed between the cubic and orthorhombic calculations reported here.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gfac_711664a6a8574817 = deduction(
    [gcn_ec768b9675814820, gcn_5868b15c687043a9],
    gcn_8c3c520295d7488c,
    reason="1. State the computational approach used and define notation: the one-shot GW quasiparticle method is denoted $G_{0}W_{0}$ (an instance of many-body perturbation theory in the GW approximation) and spin–orbit coupling is explicitly included; calculations were performed with the all-electron FLEUR and SPEX codes, which implement the $G_{0}W_{0}$ method and include spin–orbit coupling. \n[36],[37],[38]\n\n2. Explain the purpose of using $G_{0}W_{0}$ for comparison with ARPES: $G_{0}W_{0}$ yields quasiparticle self-energy corrections to electronic states and therefore produces quasiparticle band structures and band gaps that are directly comparable to ARPES spectra; these $G_{0}W_{0}$ calculations include electron–electron correlation but do not include electron–phonon (polaronic) self-energy contributions, so they provide a \"bare-band\" reference in searches for polaronic mass enhancement.\n\n3. Report the $G_{0}W_{0}$ result for the cubic crystal structure and define symbols: for the cubic structural model (with lattice parameter 6.017 Å taken from the cited structural data), the $G_{0}W_{0}$ calculation evaluated the valence-band maximum (VBM) at the R point and, along the X–R direction, yields a valence-band hole effective mass $m_{h}^{*}=0.15\\ m_{0}$ and a quasiparticle band gap of $1.74\\,$eV. The labels $m_{h}^{*}$ and $m_{0}$ are as defined above and the band gap is the energy difference between valence-band maximum and conduction-band minimum in the $G_{0}W_{0}$ quasiparticle spectrum. \nFig. 1\n\n4. Report the $G_{0}W_{0}$ result for the orthorhombic structural unit cell and note methodological details and caveats: a $G_{0}W_{0}$ calculation performed for an orthorhombic unit cell, with a Wannierization procedure applied for the valence band only (i.e., maximally-localized Wannier functions used for the valence manifold), yields an averaged hole effective mass over crystallographic directions of $m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\ m_{0}$ and a quasiparticle band gap of $2.09\\,$eV; the authors note that because Wannierization was only performed for the valence band there is a possibility that the effective mass is slightly overestimated in the orthorhombic calculation, but they believe such overestimation is limited. \nFig. S4\n\n5. Summarize the relationship of these calculations to electron-phonon coupling: explicitly state that the reported $G_{0}W_{0}$ quasiparticle band gaps and effective masses include electron–electron correlation effects but omit electron–phonon (polaronic) self-energy contributions, so any discrepancy between $G_{0}W_{0}$ masses and experiment could be indicative of additional electron–phonon renormalization but the $G_{0}W_{0}$ numbers themselves do not contain such polaronic mass enhancement.",
    prior=0.95,
)
gcn_762777de8c644c17 = claim(
    "The experimental hole effective mass m_{h}^{*}=0.203\\pm0.016\\,m_{0} and the orthorhombic one-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle hole mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} agree within the stated experimental uncertainty and the acknowledged computational caveats (such as partial Wannier interpolation and method sensitivity); therefore the ARPES-observed effective mass can be accounted for by electron–electron correlation effects already included in the one-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle description and does not require invoking an additional electron–phonon (Fröhlich-type large-polaron) mass renormalization to explain the measured value. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="G0W0 explains ARPES without extra Fröhlich renorm",
    lkm_id="gcn_762777de8c644c17",
    lkm_original="The experimental hole effective mass m_{h}^{*}=0.203\\pm0.016\\,m_{0} and the orthorhombic one-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle hole mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} agree within the stated experimental uncertainty and the acknowledged computational caveats (such as partial Wannier interpolation and method sensitivity); therefore the ARPES-observed effective mass can be accounted for by electron–electron correlation effects already included in the one-shot G_{0}W_{0} quasiparticle description and does not require invoking an additional electron–phonon (Fröhlich-type large-polaron) mass renormalization to explain the measured value.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_1fc9a84fbc6e4a1b = claim(
    "Cesium lead bromide (CsPbBr_{3}) undergoes crystallographic phase changes with temperature and adopts an orthorhombic ground-state structure at room temperature, yet ARPES band dispersions measured at room temperature can in practice resemble higher-symmetry cubic-phase dispersions for some momentum-space cuts; therefore using an orthorhombic-structure G_{0}W_{0} calculation that yields m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} for direct quantitative comparison with room-temperature ARPES data assumes that the orthorhombic theoretical band structure is an appropriate representation of the electronic states probed in the ARPES experiment, and further assumes that any difference in structural symmetry between the theoretical model and the actual electronic-state symmetry sampled by ARPES does not change the effective mass by an amount comparable to the experimental–theoretical difference being evaluated. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="Orthorhombic model comparison assumption",
    lkm_id="gcn_1fc9a84fbc6e4a1b",
    lkm_original="Cesium lead bromide (CsPbBr_{3}) undergoes crystallographic phase changes with temperature and adopts an orthorhombic ground-state structure at room temperature, yet ARPES band dispersions measured at room temperature can in practice resemble higher-symmetry cubic-phase dispersions for some momentum-space cuts; therefore using an orthorhombic-structure G_{0}W_{0} calculation that yields m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} for direct quantitative comparison with room-temperature ARPES data assumes that the orthorhombic theoretical band structure is an appropriate representation of the electronic states probed in the ARPES experiment, and further assumes that any difference in structural symmetry between the theoretical model and the actual electronic-state symmetry sampled by ARPES does not change the effective mass by an amount comparable to the experimental–theoretical difference being evaluated.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gcn_e808f6450bfc4207 = claim(
    "A Fröhlich-type large-polaron mass renormalization of approximately 50% applied to the orthorhombic one-shot G_{0}W_{0} bare-band hole mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} would increase the mass to about 0.339\\,m_{0}; given the experimentally measured hole mass 0.203\\pm0.016\\,m_{0} reported here, such a 50% enhancement would exceed the experimental value by roughly 0.136\\,m_{0}, which corresponds to more than eight times the quoted experimental standard deviation, and therefore a 50% polaronic renormalization of that magnitude would be readily detectable as a statistically significant discrepancy between the ARPES measurement and the orthorhombic G_{0}W_{0} bare-band reference under the present uncertainty assumptions. [@Sajedi2022]",
    title="50 percent polaron mass would overshoot",
    lkm_id="gcn_e808f6450bfc4207",
    lkm_original="A Fröhlich-type large-polaron mass renormalization of approximately 50% applied to the orthorhombic one-shot G_{0}W_{0} bare-band hole mass m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\,m_{0} would increase the mass to about 0.339\\,m_{0}; given the experimentally measured hole mass 0.203\\pm0.016\\,m_{0} reported here, such a 50% enhancement would exceed the experimental value by roughly 0.136\\,m_{0}, which corresponds to more than eight times the quoted experimental standard deviation, and therefore a 50% polaronic renormalization of that magnitude would be readily detectable as a statistically significant discrepancy between the ARPES measurement and the orthorhombic G_{0}W_{0} bare-band reference under the present uncertainty assumptions.",
    source_paper="paper:867765810263752934",
    provenance_source="lkm",
)
gfac_9a0ea3ef46b042d4 = deduction(
    [gcn_1fc9a84fbc6e4a1b, gcn_e808f6450bfc4207],
    gcn_762777de8c644c17,
    reason="1. Take as known the experimentally determined hole effective mass at the VBM: $m_{h}^{*}=0.203\\pm0.016\\ m_{0}$ as established from photon-energy-dependent ARPES at the R point ($h\\nu=29\\,$eV) (this is the result established earlier and treated here as an input).\n\n2. Take as known the orthorhombic $G_{0}W_{0}$ quasiparticle hole effective mass: $m_{h}^{*}=0.226\\ m_{0}$ with quasiparticle band gap $2.09\\,$eV as obtained from the orthorhombic $G_{0}W_{0}$ calculation (this is the theoretical result established earlier and treated here as an input).\n\n3. Compare the experimental and orthorhombic-theory masses numerically and state the authors' characterization of the agreement: the experimental mass $0.203\\pm0.016\\ m_{0}$ and the orthorhombic $G_{0}W_{0}$ mass $0.226\\ m_{0}$ differ by $0.023\\ m_{0}$ (about an $11\\%$ relative difference), and the authors describe these values as \"almost identical\" or \"in close agreement within uncertainties and computational caveats\" (the authors explicitly state the near equality of the experimental and orthorhombic-theory effective masses in the manuscript abstract and conclusions). \n[39]\n\n4. Invoke the methodological fact that $G_{0}W_{0}$ calculations include electron–electron correlation but explicitly do not include electron–phonon (polaronic) self-energy contributions, and explain the logical implication: because the orthorhombic $G_{0}W_{0}$ mass $0.226\\ m_{0}$ (which excludes polaronic mass renormalization by construction) already closely matches the experimentally observed mass $0.203\\pm0.016\\ m_{0}$, there is no remaining unexplained mass enhancement in the ARPES data that must be attributed to large-polaron formation (i.e., an additional Fröhlich polaronic mass renormalization is not required to reconcile theory and experiment).\n\n5. State the authors' conclusion about the physical origin of the observed effective mass: the effective mass observed in ARPES can be accounted for by electron–electron correlation effects already included in the $G_{0}W_{0}$ quasiparticle description, and therefore the ARPES-observed effective mass does not provide evidence of a residual mass enhancement that must be attributed to large-polaron formation. The authors explicitly conclude that large-polaron formation cannot be concluded from the photoemission data because the $G_{0}W_{0}$ \"bare-band\" theory already explains the measured mass. \nFig. 3\n\n6. Record the authors' stated caveats and limitations relevant to this inference: the orthorhombic calculation used Wannierization for the valence band only, which could slightly overestimate the effective mass, and there exist computational variations in $G_{0}W_{0}$ implementations and convergence (the authors benchmark and discuss differences with prior GW results in their Supplemental Material); these computational caveats are acknowledged by the authors but judged insufficient to alter the primary conclusion that no additional polaronic mass enhancement is required to explain the ARPES effective mass. \nFig. S4",
    prior=0.95,
)
